The HD 143105 Exoplanetary System


Overview

HD 143105 is a star with 1.51 times the mass of the Sun, and NaN times its radius. It is located 152.57 light years away from the solar system.

HD 143105 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the HD 143105 system


HD 143105 b

HD 143105 b was discovered by the Haute-Provence Observatory observatory, in 2016-04, using the radial velocity method. Its semi-major axis is 0.04 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of HD 143105 b is 384.780 times the mass of Earth. The radius of HD 143105 b is 13.700 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, HD 143105 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
